The basic economics=C2=A0of credit cards go something like this:=09Banks th=
at issue credit cards generally make money from the fees that merchants pay=
 to accept cards. Say those fees are 2%: If you buy a thing for $100 with a=
 credit card, you pay $100, the seller gets $98, and your bank keeps $2.
  [6]
=09Banks attract customers by rebating them a portion of those fees as =E2=
=80=9Crewards=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Ccash back.=E2=80=9D Perhaps your bank gi=
ves you back $1 on that transaction, and keeps the other $1 itself.=09In a =
competitive market, banks attract customers by rebating them=C2=A0more than=
 all=C2=A0of the fees, on certain types of transactions, with the hope that=
 the customers will like that offer but mostly use the cards for other tran=
sactions. =E2=80=9CRebating interchange to earn share of wallet,=E2=80=9D P=
atrick McKenzie calls it: =E2=80=9CSay, for example, the card rebates 1.5%,=
 but only for =E2=80=A6 bookstores. Any bookstore. For all other transactio=
ns, it is 1%. The thing you would love with this offering is to preferentia=
lly attract people who are very emotionally invested in being readers and w=
ho spends very little of [their] on-this-card wallet on books. The emotiona=
l investment in the story the card offers brings the customer in; the blend=
ed cost to acquire the customer is closer to [the] 1% industry standard and=
 not to the 1.5% headline number.=E2=80=9D=09So a bank might offer, like, =
=E2=80=9C3% cash back on books, 1% on everything else,=E2=80=9D and you say=
 =E2=80=9Cooh that sounds good,=E2=80=9D get the card, and buy $40 worth of=
 books and $40,000 of everything else. Then the bank is making money from y=
ou: It makes 1% (its 2% fee minus 1% cash back) on most of your transaction=
s, and loses 1% (its 2% fee minus 3% cash back) on a small but emotionally =
salient minority of them.=09Also of course if you carry a balance, by not p=
aying off your card every month, the bank makes a lot of money by charging =
you interest.
  [7]
=09Conversely, if you=C2=A0get this card, buy $40,000 worth of books, and=
=C2=A0do all of your other spending on other cards, the bank is losing a lo=
t of money on you: It loses 1% on every transaction. This is called =E2=80=
=9Cadverse selection.=E2=80=9DMcKenzie=E2=80=99s bookstore=C2=A0example is =
somewhat fanciful,
  [8]
=C2=A0and really to stand out many issuers offer big rebates on more typica=
lly popular=C2=A0categories like gas, groceries, restaurants, etc. Some cat=
egory where people think =E2=80=9Coh I pay for that=C2=A0all the time, that=
 card will really help me.=E2=80=9DBut you can take this too far. You don=
=E2=80=99t want the category to be too good! You don=E2=80=99t want to offe=
r high rewards on a category where your customers=C2=A0really do=C2=A0spend=
 all their money.=C2=A0The Wall Street Journal reports:In 2022, Wells [Farg=
o & Co.] launched a credit card with Bilt Technologies, a fintech startup w=
ith big-name backers including Blackstone and Mastercard. The co-branded ca=
rd came with a rare perk: Users can pay for rent with it without incurring =
fees from their landlords while also earning rewards points. More than one =
million accounts were activated in the first 18 months, many by young adult=
s.=C2=A0But Wells is losing as much as $10 million every month on the progr=
am as savvy customers flock to the card, according to current and former em=
ployees.=C2=A0Oops. The economics of=C2=A0the rent transaction itself=C2=A0=
are, for the bank, horrific:There is a reason why credit cards hadn=E2=80=
=99t gained traction in the rent sector until Bilt came along. Most landlor=
ds didn=E2=80=99t accept them because they refuse to pay card fees that get=
 pocketed by the banks issuing them and often run between 2% and 3%.Bilt st=
ructured the card so landlords won=E2=80=99t incur the fees. Wells instead =
eats much of that.=C2=A0About six months after the credit card was launched=
, Wells began paying Bilt a fee of about 0.80% of each rent transaction, ev=
en though the bank isn=E2=80=99t collecting interchange fees from landlords=
.=C2=A0Wells earns interchange fees every time people use the card to pay f=
or anything but rent and splits those fees with Bilt.It=E2=80=99s like a re=
wards card that pays 0% for everything else, but 3% cash back (sent to your=
 landlord) for rent transactions. If you hear that pitch, think =E2=80=9Che=
y that=E2=80=99s a good idea,=E2=80=9D get the card, and use it mostly to p=
ay for stuff other than rent, it probably works out okay for Wells Fargo. I=
f you also carry a balance, and Wells Fargo gets to charge you a huge inter=
est rate on the balance, it probably works out great.But =E2=80=A6=C2=A0it=
=E2=80=99s a rent credit card? If you are getting this card, probably you a=
re using it more to pay rent than for anything else? And most people, you k=
now,=C2=A0budget to pay their rent each month, which might make them less l=
ikely to carry a balance. And in fact:The bank assumed around 65% of card-p=
urchase volume would be nonrent, generating interchange-fee revenue. The re=
ality is inverted.=C2=A0Wells expected that around half to three-fourths of=
 dollars charged to the card would carry over from month to month, generati=
ng interest charges. The reality ranges between around 15% and 25%.=C2=A0I=
=C2=A0suppose there were other attractions:Some Wells employees thought the=
 proposition was crazy, but the bank needed a win and figured Bilt would ga=
rner buzz and help attract younger customers. A deal also presented mortgag=
e cross-selling opportunities. Bilt=E2=80=99s cardholders will ultimately w=
ant to become homeowners, the thought process at Wells went, and the bank w=
ould be well-positioned to give them mortgages.=C2=A0That hasn=E2=80=99t co=
me to pass, and at any rate, Wells has pulled back from mortgage lending.Ah=
, well.
