One thing that I sometimes think is that the US Securities and Exchange Com=
mission would prefer never to think about Elon Musk again. I assume that th=
e SEC is perfectly fond of a lot of the people it regulates because they ar=
e basically cooperative rule-followers, and I assume that the SEC is absolu=
tely=C2=A0overjoyed=C2=A0by a lot of scofflaws and fraudsters, because it i=
s very fun for regulators to bring cases against scofflaws. Like when Terra=
 collapsed, I am sure that the SEC had to go around looking sad and angry a=
nd saying =E2=80=9Cwe are always unhappy when investors are defrauded, and =
we will carefully investigate to see what laws were broken,=E2=80=9D but in=
 private I bet they were thrilled, because that case is funny.But Elon Musk=
 is different. Elon Musk is constantly pushing the boundaries of=C2=A0the s=
ecurities laws, but in complicated ways that are arguably allowed. He=E2=80=
=99s not running around doing funny frauds; he=E2=80=99s running around twe=
eting ambiguous winking things. And he is maximally aggressive, and hires m=
aximally aggressive lawyers, and is politically influential. So Musk will d=
o some weird thing, and people will go to the SEC being like =E2=80=9Cisn=
=E2=80=99t this illegal,=E2=80=9D and the SEC will mutter =E2=80=9CI mean=
=C2=A0we=C2=A0think so,=E2=80=9D but if they actually bring a case about it=
 it will cost a lot of time and money and be very grinding and unpleasant, =
and the legal arguments will be difficult and novel,=C2=A0and they might lo=
se, and also everyone who works on the case will be blackballed from all th=
e law firms that Elon Musk uses. It=E2=80=99s a mess.But=C2=A0not=C2=A0brin=
ging the case is also very unsatisfying: It sets bad precedents, undermines=
 the SEC=E2=80=99s regulatory program, and leads to people like me going ar=
ound saying =E2=80=9Cwhy on earth did Elon Musk get away with obviously vio=
lating the disclosure rules when he bought Twitter?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0The SEC c=
annot solve the Elon Musk problem by ignoring him, because he keeps doing s=
tuff.What the SEC would like, I suspect, is for him to keep doing stuff but=
=C2=A0vanish from their jurisdiction. Taking=C2=A0all his companies private=
 would help, probably, though the SEC does have jurisdiction over private c=
ompanies and he=E2=80=99d still find ways to enrage them. Moving the compan=
ies=C2=A0to Mars would be better. No SEC jurisdiction on Mars. Let the Mart=
ian authorities deal with him.I also think this a little bit about the Dela=
ware Court of Chancery? Like, every 20 minutes, Elon Musk does some weird b=
orderline corporate governance thing, which the board of directors of Tesla=
 Inc.
  [9]
=C2=A0and most of its shareholders love and heartily endorse. But some smal=
l shareholder says =E2=80=9Cwait this is an obvious conflict of interest,=
=E2=80=9D and sues, and then everyone gets hauled into Delaware court for a=
 hard-fought, long-running, contentious, expensive court battle. And the De=
laware court is confronted with a mess:=09Musk has done a thing that compan=
ies do not normally do, that does not comply with best practices, that no l=
awyer would advise.=09But is it=C2=A0actually illegal?=C2=A0Meh, it is bord=
erline and complicated and novel.=09Most shareholders seem fine with it, an=
d the stock keeps going up.=09Allowing him to do the thing undermines Delaw=
are=E2=80=99s promise to provide predictable corporate law that protects mi=
nority shareholders.=09Preventing him from doing the thing undermines Delaw=
are=E2=80=99s promise to provide predictable corporate law that=C2=A0enhanc=
es shareholder value.So, in 2022, Musk won a long-running Delaware case ove=
r a merger between Tesla and SolarCity Corp., another public company that h=
e controlled. That merger was=C2=A0absurdly=C2=A0conflicted =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
Musk owned two companies and merged them, and Tesla=E2=80=99s board basical=
ly did whatever he asked, instead of setting up an independent special comm=
ittee to negotiate the deal=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but also shareholders were =
basically happy. But one disgruntled Tesla shareholder sued, saying that Te=
sla overpaid for SolarCity to bail out Musk=E2=80=99s own investment, and a=
 judge ultimately found that, uh,=C2=A0Musk probably should have just been =
more normal
  [10]
:The process employed by the Tesla Board to negotiate and ultimately recomm=
end the Acquisition was far from perfect. Elon was more involved in the pro=
cess than a conflicted fiduciary should be. And conflicts among other Tesla=
 Board members were not completely neutralized.But Tesla=E2=80=99s stock wa=
s way=C2=A0up since the deal, so no harm no foul:The preponderance of the e=
vidence reveals that Tesla paid a fair price=E2=80=94SolarCity was, at a mi=
nimum, worth what Tesla paid for it, and the Acquisition otherwise was high=
ly beneficial to Tesla. =E2=80=A6While the synergistic effects of the Acqui=
sition are still unfolding, the astronomic rise in Tesla=E2=80=99s stock pr=
ice post-Acquisition is noteworthy.=E2=80=9CI=C2=A0cannot help but observe,=
=E2=80=9D wrote the judge,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthat Elon (and the rest of the Tes=
la Board members) likely could have avoided this expensive and time-consumi=
ng litigation had they just adopted more objectively evident procedural pro=
tections.=E2=80=9D Just be normal! Don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0create=C2=A0a complic=
ated novel difficult case when you can do things the normal way and have it=
 be fine!Also in 2022, there was Musk=E2=80=99s takeover of Twitter Inc., w=
here he signed a merger agreement, changed his mind, and tried to get out o=
f it with silly arguments. Eventually he gave up and closed the deal, but t=
here was a period when people wondered: What would happen if a Delaware jud=
ge ordered him to come up with $44 billion and close the deal, and he said =
no? I was making jokes about =E2=80=9CChancery jail,=E2=80=9D but they were=
 nervous jokes. Delaware=E2=80=99s main export, as a state, is predictable =
merger rules, and Elon Musk does not do well with predictability.And then t=
here was the dispute over Musk=E2=80=99s 2018 pay package, which we have ta=
lked about more recently. Earlier this year, a Delaware judge ruled that Mu=
sk=E2=80=99s 2018 decision to pay himself a huge slice of Tesla options =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0at one point worth more than $56 billion =E2=80=94=C2=A0was inv=
alid, that Tesla=E2=80=99s board was too controlled by him to make an indep=
endent decision about his pay, and that Tesla=E2=80=99s shareholders approv=
ed it without being fully informed.I thought this was a weird decision. =E2=
=80=9CThere is something awkward,=E2=80=9D I wrote,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cabout a j=
udge second-guessing the CEO compensation decisions of the board of directo=
rs of a $600 billion company, even if, yes, it=E2=80=99s the board of Tesla=
.=E2=80=9D Tesla got a lot of value for that $56 billion =E2=80=94=C2=A0at =
its peak its market value was up by $1 trillion since the pay package was a=
warded =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the shareholders mostly approved. And last week T=
esla put the question to a vote of shareholders again, now fully informed b=
y the judge=E2=80=99s objections, and the shareholders again overwhelmingly=
 voted in favor of giving Musk his money.Still I sympathize with the judge:=
 Musk decided how much to pay himself, it was the largest executive pay pac=
kage ever, and a completely subservient board of directors said =E2=80=9Csu=
re here you go.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s not really ideal corporate governan=
ce. Endorsing this pay package would have been a bit troubling. But rejecti=
ng it was worse: The decision clearly reduced shareholder value, and was cl=
early not what a majority of shareholders wanted. The court went a bit too =
far, protecting shareholders from bad governance in ways that they didn=E2=
=80=99t want and that didn=E2=80=99t help them.Anyway, as we discussed last=
 week, Tesla went back to the shareholders for two votes. One was to re-app=
rove Musk=E2=80=99s 2018 pay package, which they did. And the other was to =
approve moving Tesla=E2=80=99s state of incorporation to Texas, which they =
did by an even larger majority. =E2=80=9CTesla has submitted all filings to=
 effectuate its conversion into a Texas corporation and can confirm that th=
e Company is now incorporated in Texas,=E2=80=9D it announced on Thursday.O=
ne obvious takeaway here is that Delaware court=C2=A0overreached, that shar=
eholders rejected Delaware law, and that this is bad for Delaware in the lo=
ng run.=C2=A0Perhaps now Texas is the more business-friendly place to be. =
=E2=80=9CThe Big Loser in Tesla=E2=80=99s Shareholder Vote Is Delaware,=E2=
=80=9D writes the Wall Street Journal: =E2=80=9CBy voting to leave the Firs=
t State, shareholders could be ratifying the view among some that Delaware=
=E2=80=99s shareholder protections have gone too far, some legal experts sa=
id.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0And I think there=E2=80=99s some truth to that. Maybe oth=
er companies=C2=A0will=C2=A0follow Musk=E2=80=99s lead and move out of Dela=
ware, to reduce the risk of shareholder litigation that gives disgruntled s=
mall shareholders finicky procedural protections at the cost of reducing va=
lue for everyone else.
  [11]
=C2=A0Though maybe not; maybe this is Musk-specific. =E2=80=9CMaybe=C2=A0El=
on Musk is a special case,=E2=80=9D I wrote last week,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cand sh=
areholders rationally want him to be allowed to do whatever he wants=E2=80=
=9D; shareholders of other companies, not run by Elon Musk, might prefer De=
