his disclosure or misleading the market about his plans.=C2=A0I once estima=
ted that =E2=80=9Che saved $143 million on those purchases by filing his fo=
rm late,=E2=80=9D and the rules are just really clear, so I remain puzzled =
that the SEC hasn=E2=80=99t brought a case yet. I suppose they are trying t=
o figure out if he broke the rules intentionally, or just because he didn=
=E2=80=99t care.Second, we talked a few weeks ago about news reports that M=
usk redirected a shipment of Nvidia chips from Tesla to X Corp. (formerly T=
witter), as his own ambitions for artificial intelligence have increasingly=
 shifted from Tesla to xAI (yet another company he controls). Probably most=
 Tesla shareholders are fine with that, and certainly Tesla=E2=80=99s=C2=A0=
board is fine with that; they=E2=80=99re fine with whatever Musk does. But =
it=E2=80=99s an obvious conflict of interest, and there it is in the newspa=
per, so of course a shareholder sued. Last week. In Delaware Chancery Court=
. =E2=80=9CGetting in under the wire before the Texas move,=E2=80=9D tweete=
d law professor Ann Lipton. If I were a Delaware chancellor, I=E2=80=99d be=
 trying to make this case Texas=E2=80=99s problem too.
 =20
   =20
      Werewolf
   =20
 =20
One appeal of cryptocurrency is that it might be a=C2=A0better=C2=A0form of=
 currency than traditional=C2=A0currencies. Cryptocurrencies, the argument =
goes, can do stuff that traditional currencies can=E2=80=99t do: They can b=
e transferred peer to peer without any intermediaries, they can be carried =
in electronic form without a bank account, they can be =E2=80=9Cprogrammabl=
e money,=E2=80=9D they can=C2=A0be elements in smart contracts.=C2=A0But an=
other appeal is that it might be=C2=A0worse than traditional currencies. I =
am not kidding, and this is not a trivial appeal! It is not hard to imagine=
 use cases in which =E2=80=9Ccurrency, but worse=E2=80=9D is what you want:=
 You want a currency that is more restricted or more contingent than dollar=
s. Giving your kids an allowance of 10 AllowanceBucks =E2=80=94=C2=A0dollar=
s, but they can only be spent on age-appropriate goods=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0=
might be better than giving them an unrestricted $10. Or part of the case f=
or central bank digital currencies is that they could have negative interes=
t rates: =E2=80=9Cdollars, but 1% of them vanish every month.=E2=80=9D That=
=E2=80=99s worse than a dollar! For you, I mean. But the essential fact of =
currency is that it represents a claim on somebody else: A dollar in your h=
ands represents an=C2=A0obligation of society to give you $1 worth of stuff=
. A slightly worse currency represents a slightly weaker obligation, and so=
metimes that=E2=80=99s what you want. Fine-tuning a financial system might =
benefit from having some currencies that are=C2=A0more=C2=A0powerful and us=
eful than dollars, but also some that are=C2=A0less=C2=A0powerful and usefu=
l.Okay fine I=E2=80=99m partially kidding; here=E2=80=99s a press release I=
 got:JUNE 16 - Werewolf Coin, a cryptocurrency that can only be used during=
 the full moon, publicly launched today.A project by an anonymous artist, W=
erewolf Coin can be transferred for 24 hours before each full moon and for =
24 hours after each full moon. Astronomically, a full moon refers to the mo=
ment when the Moon is exactly 180 degrees away from the Sun.The cryptocurre=
ncy can be minted on=C2=A0https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/357=
46803.259295/aHR0cHM6Ly93ZXJld29sZmNvLmluLA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB71ed34=
5b which also features a lunar calendar.I cannot think of any actual reason=
 this would be better than regular money.
