  [1] The math on that is that there were 664,284 shares of SilverSun outst=
anding before the transaction (adjusting for an 8-for-1 reverse stock split=
), and the Jacobs group got convertible preferred stock and warrants that c=
onvert into 438,014,750 shares, or about 99.85%. Jacobs himself reports an =
89.86% ownership; the minority investors get another 10%, and the public pr=
e-deal SilverSun shareholders have the other 0.15%. These numbers don=E2=80=
=99t quite foot to the market cap ratios because the Jacobs group got (1) c=
onvertible preferred stock that converts into 197,106,637 shares, and is es=
sentially the same as common stock plus (2) warrants, which have to be exer=
cised separately at strike prices ranging from $4.566 to $13.698 per share.=
 In other words, the Jacobs group report owning *more* stock than you=E2=80=
=99d expect based on a $1 billion investment, but some of that is stock und=
erlying unexercised warrants.


  [2] See page 23 of SilverSun=E2=80=99s 10-Q for more details. Briefly: Th=
e original December deal between Jacobs and SilverSun was that he would tak=
e control of SilverSun, and SilverSun would pay a $2.5 million dividend to =
its shareholders and also spin out its legacy business to them. Then in Apr=
il the deal was revised to pay a $17.4 million dividend and *not* spin out =
the legacy business. =E2=80=9CSilverSun=E2=80=99s existing operations will =
be retained=E2=80=9D by QXO, is apparently the plan. Those existing operati=
ons generated $1.7 million of net income on $54.4 million of revenue in 202=
3: SilverSun is/was a *teeny* company, but unlike a lot of reverse-merger t=
argets it is not a *defunct* one. I couldn=E2=80=99t tell you what it does/=
did, though the 10-K says that it is =E2=80=9Cengaged in providing transfor=
mational business management applications and technologies and professional=
 consulting services to small and medium size companies, primarily in the m=
anufacturing, distribution and service industries,=E2=80=9D and is =E2=80=
=9Ca value-added reseller of business application software.=E2=80=9D I gues=
s QXO could keep distributing software as well as building materials, why n=
ot.


  [3] The co-investors are locked up until 2029, and Jacobs presumably woul=
d need a registration statement to sell his shares. Also they don=E2=80=99t=
 have common shares; they have preferred stock and warrants that can conver=
t into common.


  [4] This is not a good way of doing the math, because a lot of those warr=
ants have exercise prices, so more cash would come in to get to that $110 b=
illion valuation. It=E2=80=99s the right ballpark though.


  [5] Again, slightly off =E2=80=94 there are warrants, etc. =E2=80=94 but =
essentially correct. Incidentally that=E2=80=99s about a 100% premium to th=
e $4.566 per share that Jacobs and the initial seed investors got last Dece=
mber: This company is a hot ticket among institutional investors too!


  [6] All of this is oversimplified: The number is not a flat 2% (and that=
=E2=80=99s probably a bit high for most transaction categories), and the fe=
e is split among the issuing bank, the merchant bank, the card network and =
other intermediaries.


  [7] Unless you default.


  [8] Or else a reference to one particular bookstore.


  [9] He does weird stuff at his private companies too, but no one really s=
ues.


  [10] Because Musk=E2=80=99s brother Kimbal was also involved in this case=
, the judge=E2=80=99s opinion calls Elon Musk =E2=80=9CElon=E2=80=9D rather=
 than =E2=80=9CMusk.=E2=80=9D


  [11] Ann Lipton writes: =E2=80=9COne story is, [Tesla=E2=80=99s instituti=
onal shareholders] agree that fiduciary litigation is rent-seeking, contrar=
y to shareholder interests, and does nothing more than distract boards from=
 doing their actual jobs.  In this story, Tesla=E2=80=99s shareholders vote=
d to limit the nuisances that threatened the ability of Elon Musk to run th=
e company as he sees fit =E2=80=93 in a manner that would ultimately maximi=
ze the benefits to Tesla shareholders.  In other words, fiduciary litigatio=
n is too powerful, in that it inhibits too much managerial flexibility by i=
mposing inappropriate one-size-fits-all standards.=E2=80=9D


  [12] The Journal article goes on: =E2=80=9CAn alternative, however, is th=
at Musk is simply so important that investors are willing to take a chance =
on Texas. =E2=80=98I do think that Elon Musk is this singular figure,=E2=80=
=99 said Renee Zaytsev, a corporate- and securities-law attorney at Boies S=
chiller Flexner. =E2=80=98Is Tesla what other companies are looking to, to =
decide where they=E2=80=99re going to incorporate or how they=E2=80=99re go=
ing to run their governance? Probably not.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D


