</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic economics=C2=A0of credit car=
ds go something like this:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; paddin=
g-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Banks t=
hat issue credit cards generally make money from the fees that merchants pa=
y to accept cards. Say those fees are 2%: If you buy a thing for $100 with =
a credit card, you pay $100, the seller gets $98, and your bank keeps $2.<a=
 class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpa=
rent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a></li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Banks attract customers by re=
bating them a portion of those fees as =E2=80=9Crewards=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=
=9Ccash back.=E2=80=9D Perhaps your bank gives you back $1 on that transact=
ion, and keeps the other $1 itself.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;=
">In a competitive market, banks attract customers by rebating them=C2=A0<e=
m>more than all=C2=A0</em>of the fees, on certain types of transactions, wi=
th the hope that the customers will like that offer but mostly use the card=
s for other transactions. =E2=80=9CRebating interchange to earn share of wa=
llet,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/357=
46803.259295/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYml0c2Fib3V0bW9uZXkuY29tL2FyY2hpdmUvYW5hdG9teS=
1vZi1jcmVkaXQtY2FyZC1yZXdhcmRzLXByb2dyYW1zLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB547a2=
161" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">Patrick McKenzie calls it</a>: =E2=80=9CSay, for example, the =
card rebates 1.5%, but only for =E2=80=A6 bookstores. Any bookstore. For al=
l other transactions, it is 1%. The thing you would love with this offering=
 is to preferentially attract people who are very emotionally invested in b=
eing readers and who spends very little of [their] on-this-card wallet on b=
ooks. The emotional investment in the story the card offers brings the cust=
omer in; the blended cost to acquire the customer is closer to [the] 1% ind=
ustry standard and not to the 1.5% headline number.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li sty=
le=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">So a bank might offer, like, =E2=80=9C3% cash ba=
ck on books, 1% on everything else,=E2=80=9D and you say =E2=80=9Cooh that =
sounds good,=E2=80=9D get the card, and buy $40 worth of books and $40,000 =
of everything else. Then the bank is making money from you: It makes 1% (it=
s 2% fee minus 1% cash back) on most of your transactions, and loses 1% (it=
s 2% fee minus 3% cash back) on a small but emotionally salient minority of=
 them.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Also of course if you carry=
 a balance, by not paying off your card every month, the bank makes a lot o=
f money by charging you interest.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footn=
ote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !i=
mportant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;"=
>
<span>[7]</span>
</a></li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Conversely, if you=C2=A0get t=
his card, buy $40,000 worth of books, and=C2=A0<em>do all of your other spe=
nding on other cards</em>, the bank is losing a lot of money on you: It los=
es 1% on every transaction. This is called =E2=80=9Cadverse selection.=E2=
=80=9D</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">McKenzie=E2=80=99s bookstore=
=C2=A0example is somewhat fanciful,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foo=
tnote-8" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none =
!important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block=
;">
<span>[8]</span>
</a>=C2=A0and really to stand out many issuers offer big rebates on more ty=
pically popular=C2=A0categories like gas, groceries, restaurants, etc. Some=
 category where people think =E2=80=9Coh I pay for <em>that=C2=A0</em>all t=
he time, that card will really help me.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
