itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">math on that</a> is that the=
re were 664,284 shares of SilverSun outstanding before the transaction (adj=
usting for an 8-for-1 reverse stock split), and the Jacobs group got conver=
tible preferred stock and warrants that convert into 438,014,750 shares, or=
 about 99.85%. Jacobs himself reports an 89.86% ownership; the minority inv=
estors get another 10%, and the public pre-deal SilverSun shareholders have=
 the other 0.15%. These numbers don=E2=80=99t quite foot to the market cap =
ratios because the Jacobs group got (1) convertible preferred stock that co=
nverts into 197,106,637 shares, and is essentially the same as common stock=
 plus (2) warrants, which have to be exercised separately at strike prices =
ranging from $4.566 to $13.698 per share. In other words, the Jacobs group =
report owning *more* stock than you=E2=80=99d expect based on a $1 billion =
investment, but some of that is stock underlying unexercised warrants.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-2" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[2] See page 23 of <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35746803.259295/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9pe=
D9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTIzNjI3NS8wMDAxMTg1MTg1MjQwMDA0NzUvc2ls=
dmVyc3VuMjAyNDAzMzFfMTBxLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cEd21035b5" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
SilverSun=E2=80=99s 10-Q</a> for more details. Briefly: The original Decemb=
er deal between Jacobs and SilverSun was that he would take control of Silv=
erSun, and SilverSun would pay a $2.5 million dividend to its shareholders =
and also spin out its legacy business to them. Then in April the deal was r=
evised to pay a $17.4 million dividend and *not* spin out the legacy busine=
ss. =E2=80=9CSilverSun=E2=80=99s existing operations will be retained=E2=80=
=9D by QXO, is apparently the plan. Those existing operations <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35746803.259295/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTIzNjI3NS8wMDAxMTg1MTg1Mj=
QwMDAyMzcvc2lsdmVyc3VuMjAyMzEyMzFfMTBrLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cF894dc=
e38" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">generated $1.7 million of net income</a> on $54.4 million of r=
evenue in 2023: SilverSun is/was a *teeny* company, but unlike a lot of rev=
erse-merger targets it is not a *defunct* one. I couldn=E2=80=99t tell you =
what it does/did, though <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/35746803.259295/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRh=
LzEyMzYyNzUvMDAwMTE4NTE4NTI0MDAwMjM3L3NpbHZlcnN1bjIwMjMxMjMxXzEway5odG0jaTE=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe3a80de1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the 10-K says</a> that it is =
=E2=80=9Cengaged in providing transformational business management applicat=
ions and technologies and professional consulting services to small and med=
ium size companies, primarily in the manufacturing, distribution and servic=
e industries,=E2=80=9D and is =E2=80=9Ca value-added reseller of business a=
pplication software.=E2=80=9D I guess QXO could keep distributing software =
as well as building materials, why not.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-3" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[3] The co-investors are <a href=3D"https://li=
